{"title_page": "Canada Emergency Business Account", "text_new": "The '''Canadian Emergency Business Account''' ('''CEBA''') is a [[Canada|Canadian]] support program created by the [[Government of Canada]].<ref name=\"gm3br\">{{cite news |title=The three bridges Canada needs to get us across the economic chasm |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/article-the-three-bridges-canada-needs-to-get-us-across-the-economic-chasm/ |publisher=The Globe and Mail Inc |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>  The aim  of this program is to ensure that [[small business]]es have access to sufficient [[Capital (economics)|capital]] and can overcome financial hardships due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in Canada|COVID-19 pandemic]]. CEBA is included in [[Bill (law)|Bill]] C-14, which was introduced by [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Finance Minister]] [[Bill Morneau]] on April 11, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/department-finance/news/2020/04/government-introduces-covid-19-emergency-response-act-no-2-to-help-businesses-keep-canadians-in-their-jobs.html|title=Government Introduces COVID-19 Emergency Response Act, No. 2 to Help Businesses Keep Canadians in their Jobs|last=Canada|first=Department of Finance|date=2020-04-11|website=gcnws|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\nThe [[budget]] was set for $25 billion, offering [[Zero interest-rate policy|interest-free loans]] of up to $40,000 to small businesses and [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profits]].<ref name=gm3br/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ceba-cuec.ca/|title=You are being redirected...|website=ceba-cuec.ca|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> The loans will be implemented by [[financial institution]]s in cooperation with [[Export Development Canada]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Recipients that repay the balance by December 31, 2022 will receive 25% [[Debt relief|loan forgiveness]] to a maximum of $10,000.<ref name=gm3br/> The size of the loans could be increased, along with the amount forgivable.<ref name=\"gm3br\"/> The due date could also be moved into 2024 if need be.<ref name=\"gm3br\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian society]]\n[[Category:Social programs]]\n[[Category:Social security in Canada]]\n[[Category:Unemployment benefits]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada]]\n[[Category:National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n\n{{Canada-stub}}\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Canadian Emergency Business Account''' ('''CEBA''') is a [[Canada|Canadian]] support program created by the [[Government of Canada]].<ref name=\"gm3br\">{{cite news |title=The three bridges Canada needs to get us across the economic chasm |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/article-the-three-bridges-canada-needs-to-get-us-across-the-economic-chasm/ |publisher=The Globe and Mail Inc |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>  The aim  of this program is to ensure that [[small business]]es have access to sufficient [[Capital (economics)|capital]] and can overcome financial hardships due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|COVID-19 pandemic]]. CEBA is included in [[Bill (law)|Bill]] C-14, which was introduced by [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Finance Minister]] [[Bill Morneau]] on April 11, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/department-finance/news/2020/04/government-introduces-covid-19-emergency-response-act-no-2-to-help-businesses-keep-canadians-in-their-jobs.html|title=Government Introduces COVID-19 Emergency Response Act, No. 2 to Help Businesses Keep Canadians in their Jobs|last=Canada|first=Department of Finance|date=2020-04-11|website=gcnws|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\nThe [[budget]] was set for $25 billion, offering [[Zero interest-rate policy|interest-free loans]] of up to $40,000 to small businesses and [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profits]].<ref name=gm3br/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ceba-cuec.ca/|title=You are being redirected...|website=ceba-cuec.ca|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> The loans will be implemented by [[financial institution]]s in cooperation with [[Export Development Canada]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Recipients that repay the balance by December 31, 2022 will receive 25% [[Debt relief|loan forgiveness]] to a maximum of $10,000.<ref name=gm3br/> The size of the loans could be increased, along with the amount forgivable.<ref name=\"gm3br\"/> The due date could also be moved into 2024 if need be.<ref name=\"gm3br\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian society]]\n[[Category:Social programs]]\n[[Category:Social security in Canada]]\n[[Category:Unemployment benefits]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada]]\n[[Category:National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n\n{{Canada-stub}}\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "name_user": "RobertskySemi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:bypass redirect, replaced:Canadiansupport program created by theGovernment of Canada.<ref name=\"gm3br\">{{cite news |title=The three bridges Canada needs to get us across the economic chasm |url=\u230a\u230a\u230a\u230a0\u230b\u230b\u230b\u230b |p", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canada_Emergency_Business_Account"}
